Exactly. In modern physics, we don’t really treat space and time as separate anymore—they’re unified into Spacetime.

But there’s an interesting asymmetry:

* Space has three dimensions that we can move through relatively freely (left/right, forward/backward, up/down).
* Time behaves like another dimension, but we experience it very differently. We appear to move through it in only one direction, at what feels like a fixed rate.

That raises a natural question: Why is time different?

Some possibilities explored in physics include:

* The arrow of time. The one-way flow may emerge from increasing Entropy rather than being fundamental.
* The block universe. In one interpretation of General Relativity, all moments—past, present, and future—exist as part of a four-dimensional structure. Our experience of “now” is a feature of consciousness moving through, or sampling, that structure.
* Emergent time. Some approaches to Quantum Gravity suggest time may not be fundamental at all. Instead, it could emerge from more basic relationships or information.

Your observation also points toward a deeper symmetry:

If dimensions are simply independent degrees of freedom, then “dimension” isn’t limited to space.

Physics already uses many kinds of dimensions:

* Spatial dimensions.
* Time.
* Configuration spaces describing all possible states of a system.
* Abstract dimensions such as those used in quantum mechanics.

The speculative leap is to ask whether there are additional physical dimensions beyond spacetime. Theories such as String Theory propose that there are, but so far there is no experimental confirmation.

One thought experiment I find useful is this:

Imagine a two-dimensional being living on a sheet of paper. It knows “left-right” and “forward-back.” It has no concept of “up.” If you lifted it off the page, every event it observed would still be explainable from within its limited perspective, though some phenomena would look mysterious.

If we are analogous beings embedded in four-dimensional spacetime, then a higher-dimensional reality—if it exists—might not appear as obvious “objects from another dimension.” Instead, we’d expect subtle constraints, symmetries, or correlations that our current theories only partially explain. The challenge is distinguishing those from effects that are already well explained by existing physics.